## Summary

Implemented the nestable, non-singleton menu model in two new files (registered in `project.pbxproj`, IDs 0x31–0x34):

**`Bringr/MenuModel.swift`** — the generic, reusable model plus the v1 menu:
- `MenuNode` — `Identifiable` value-type tree that nests to arbitrary depth via `children` (AC1).
- `MenuChildren` — `.static([MenuNode])` or `.dynamic(@MainActor () -> [MenuNode])`; `resolvedChildren()` runs the provider so sub-wheels reflect live state (AC2).
- `MenuAction` — `.expand` / `.focusWindow(WindowID)`, extended by adding cases (AC3).
- `MenuTrigger`, `MenuDefinition` (`@MainActor protocol`), `MenuRegistry` (`[MenuTrigger: any MenuDefinition]`) — no singleton; `makeMenu(for:)` builds a fresh tree each summon, and one definition can answer both triggers (AC4).
- `WindowSwitcherMenu` — conformer that builds the apps→windows tree from `WindowEnumerator`, with each app's sub-wheel as a dynamic provider that re-queries live state on hover.

**`BringrTests/MenuModelTests.swift`** — 9 tests across all five ACs, including building the apps→windows tree from enumeration fixtures and asserting structure (AC5). Added a mutable `StubEnumerationSource` to prove the dynamic providers genuinely re-query.

**Gates:** `** BUILD SUCCEEDED **`, SwiftLint 0 violations, 34 tests pass (9 new), app launches stably with the new code linked.

Per the established pattern (US-003/004), the model is not wired into `AppDelegate` yet — nothing summons a menu until a trigger/overlay exists (US-006/007/008), so the registry and `WindowSwitcherMenu` get wired in then. No git commit created (the engine handles that).

